subsection.p:
Consider some sequence 0\lt r_1 \lt r_2 \lt \ldots of radii growing to infinity and denote by
\mathcal{K^i}=\{K^i_{j} \subset X; 1\leq j \leq N_i\}
the infinite connected components of X \setminus B(x_0,r_i). Common sense about sets implies that since we have B(x_0,r_1)\subset B(x_0,r_2)\subset \cdots then if n>m then each element of \mathcal{K}^n is contained in a unique element of \mathcal{K}^m which gives a well defined surjective function f_{nm}:\mathcal K^n \to \mathcal K ^m.

